	<h2 class="story">
		

		

		
		

		

		

		

		<span id="title-172264955" class="story-title"> <a onclick="return toggle_fh_body_wrap_return(this);"  href="//games.slashdot.org/story/23/11/18/204226/source-code-to-infocoms-text-adventure-interpreters-now-available">Source Code To Infocom's Text Adventure Interpreters Now Available</a></span>

		
		
		<!--<span class="comments commentcnt-172264955" >14</span>-->
		

		
		<!-- comment bubble -->
		
			<span class="comment-bubble"><a href="//games.slashdot.org/story/23/11/18/204226/source-code-to-infocoms-text-adventure-interpreters-now-available#comments" title="">14</a></span>
		
	</h2>
	<div class="details" id="details-172264955">
		<span class="story-details">
		<span class="story-views">
			<span class="sodify" onclick="firehose_set_options('color', 'red')" title="Filter Firehose to entries rated red or better"></span><span class="icon-beaker pop1 " alt="Popularity" title="Filter Firehose to entries rated red or better" onclick="firehose_set_options('color', 'red')"><span></span></span> 
		</span>
		</span>
		<span class="story-byline">
	
				
			Posted
				by 
		
		
			
				  EditorDavid
			
		
		

		
		
		<time id="fhtime-172264955" datetime="on Saturday November 18, 2023 @04:59PM">on Saturday November 18, 2023 @04:59PM</time>
		
		
			 from the <span class="dept-text">standing-in-an-open-field</span> dept.
		
		</span>
	</div>
</header>

<div class="body" id="fhbody-172264955">
	

	
		
		<div id="text-172264955" class="p">
			
		 	
				Slashdot reader <a href="/~Mononymous">Mononymous</a> writes: <i>Back in 2019, digital archivist Jason Scott <a href="https://games.slashdot.org/story/19/04/18/2132228/the-source-code-for-all-infocom-text-adventure-classics-has-been-released">released</a> the source code to Infocom's classic text adventures. Now the other piece of the puzzle is available: the <a href="https://github.com/erkyrath/infocom-zcode-terps">source code</a> (mostly in assembly, with some C and Pascal) to their microcomputer interpreters.

<br> <br>Infocom, publisher of the best-selling <i>Zork</i> series, ported their text adventures to most of the diverse microcomputer platforms of the 1980s by using an early virtual machine, known as the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-machine">Z-machine</a> or <i>ZIP</i>. This enabled them to sell games simultaneously for everything from the TI-99/4A to the Commodore 128. Hobbyists reverse-engineered the technology in the 1990s to create modern implementations, but now the original source code can be studied directly.</i>
		 	
		</div>

		

		

		
	</div>
